    "summary": "Character's strength: single word, \"what makes a thing itself,\" no moral baggage",
    "content": "\n**Strongest advantage of \"character\":** It is the only single-word option that captures \"what makes a thing what it is\" without triggering moral associations. In the sentence \"everything has its character\" (凡事诸物皆有其德), \"character\" reads naturally and correctly -- you immediately understand that dogs have a dog-character, humans have a human-character, pens have a pen-character. No other single English word does this as cleanly.\n\nWith 性 off the table, \"nature\" is now also viable and I would rank it equal to \"character.\" But \"character\" has one edge: \"nature\" can suggest something innate and fixed (\"it's just their nature\"), while \"character\" is more neutral on whether the property is innate or constructed -- matching the author's constructivist position.\n"
